  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering. These aim to combat money laundering at a global level and foster international cooperation. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This was one of the first major international agreements that addressed money laundering, primarily concerning the proceeds of drug trafficking. It required states to criminalize the laundering of drug money and to cooperate in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a law or convention itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body established in 1989 to develop policies to combat money laundering. It sets international standards (the FATF Recommendations) that countries are expected to implement. These recommendations cover a wide range of issues, including criminalizing money laundering, customer due diligence, record-keeping, and international cooperation. FATF's influence is significant as its recommendations are adopted by a large number of countries and are often incorporated into national legislation.  Countries that fail to comply can face sanctions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention broadened the scope of anti-money laundering efforts beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of all serious crimes committed by organized criminal groups. It requires states to criminalize money laundering related to these crimes and to cooperate internationally in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions on preventing and combating money laundering related to corruption offenses. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from corruption and to take measures to recover assets that have been laundered.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) (Strasbourg Convention):** This European convention focuses on international cooperation in combating money laundering and recovering the proceeds of crime.\n\n*   **Revised Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (2005) (Warsaw Convention):** This revised convention updates and strengthens the Strasbourg Convention, expanding its scope to include the financing of terrorism.\n\nThese international instruments provide a framework for national laws and regulations aimed at preventing and combating money laundering. They also promote international cooperation, including information sharing, mutual legal assistance, and extradition. However, the effectiveness of these laws and conventions depends on the willingness and ability of individual countries to implement and enforce them.\n",
